            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'net income?', 'answer': 'Net income is calculated as Total Revenue - Total Expenses. Example formula: =Revenue - Expenses.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'gross profit margin?','answer':  'Gross profit margin is calculated as (Gross Profit / Revenue) * 100. Example formula: = (Revenue - Cost_of_Goods_Sold) / Revenue * 100.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'operating profit margin?','answer':  'Operating profit margin is calculated as (Operating Profit / Revenue) * 100. Example formula: = Operating_Profit / Revenue * 100.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'return on assets (ROA)?', 'answer': 'ROA is calculated as Net Income / Total Assets. Example formula: = Net_Income / Total_Assets.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'return on equity (ROE)?','answer':  'ROE is calculated as Net Income / Shareholder\ Equity. Example formula: = Net_Income / Shareholder_Equity.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'debt-to-equity ratio?', 'answer': 'Debt-to-equity ratio is calculated as Total Debt / Total Equity. Example formula: = Total_Debt / Total_Equity.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'earnings per share (EPS)?', 'answer': 'EPS is calculated as (Net Income - Dividends on Preferred Stock) / Average Outstanding Shares. Example formula: = (Net_Income - Preferred_Dividends) / Average_Shares.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'current ratio?','answer':  'The current ratio is calculated as Current Assets / Current Liabilities. Example formula: = Current_Assets / Current_Liabilities.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'quick ratio?','answer':  'The quick ratio is calculated as (Current Assets - Inventory) / Current Liabilities. Example formula: = (Current_Assets - Inventory) / Current_Liabilities.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'straight-line depreciation','answer':  'Use the SLN function to calculate straight-line depreciation. Example formula: =SLN(cost, salvage, life}, where cost is the initial cost, salvage is the salvage value, and life is the number of periods.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'sum of depreciation using the DB function', 'answer': 'Use the DB function to calculate depreciation using the fixed-declining balance method. Example formula: =DB(cost, salvage, life, period, [month]).'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'PV function to calculate the present value of an investment','answer':  'Use the PV function to calculate the present value of an investment. Example formula: =PV(rate, nper, pmt, [fv], [type]}, where rate is the interest rate per period, nper is the number of periods, pmt is the payment per period, fv is the future value, and type indicates when payments are due.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'calculate the future value of an investment using the FV function', 'answer': 'Use the FV function to calculate the future value of an investment. Example formula: =FV(rate, nper, pmt, [pv], [type]}, where rate is the interest rate per period, nper is the number of periods, pmt is the payment per period, pv is the present value, and type indicates when payments are due.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'NPV function to calculate net present value','answer':  'Use the NPV function to calculate the net present value of a series of cash flows. Example formula: =NPV(rate, value1, [value2], ...}, where rate is the discount rate, and value1, value2, ... are the cash flows.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'IRR function to calculate the internal rate of return', 'answer': 'Use the IRR function to calculate the internal rate of return for a series of cash flows. Example formula: =IRR(value1, [value2], ...}, where value1, value2, ... are the cash flows.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'XNPV function to calculate the net present value with non-periodic cash flows','answer':  'Use the XNPV function to calculate the net present value with non-periodic cash flows. Example formula: =XNPV(rate, values, dates}, where rate is the discount rate, values are the cash flows, and dates are the corresponding dates of the cash flows.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'XIRR function to calculate the internal rate of return for non-periodic cash flows','answer':  'Use the XIRR function to calculate the internal rate of return for non-periodic cash flows. Example formula: =XIRR(values, dates}, where values are the cash flows and dates are the corresponding dates.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'calculate loan payments using the PMT function','answer':  'Use the PMT function to calculate the loan payment for a loan based on constant payments and a constant interest rate. Example formula: =PMT(rate, nper, pv, [fv], [type]}, where rate is the interest rate per period, nper is the number of periods, pv is the present value, fv is the future value, and type indicates when payments are due.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'calculate the interest expense on a loan using the IPMT function', 'answer': 'Use the IPMT function to calculate the interest expense for a particular period of a loan. Example formula: =IPMT(rate, per, nper, pv, [fv], [type]}, where rate is the interest rate per period, per is the period number, nper is the total number of periods, pv is the present value, fv is the future value, and type indicates when payments are due.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'calculate the principal repayment on a loan using the PPMT function', 'answer': 'Use the PPMT function to calculate the principal repayment for a particular period of a loan. Example formula: =PPMT(rate, per, nper, pv, [fv], [type]}, where rate is the interest rate per period, per is the period number, nper is the total number of periods, pv is the present value, fv is the future value, and type indicates when payments are due.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'DURATION function to calculate the Macaulay duration of a bond','answer':  'Use the DURATION function to calculate the Macaulay duration of a bond. Example formula: =DURATION(settlement, maturity, coupon, yld, frequency, [basis]}, where settlement is the bond\'s settlement date, maturity is the bond\'s maturity date, coupon is the bond\'s annual coupon rate, yld is the bond\'s annual yield, frequency is the number of coupon payments per year, and basis is the day count basis.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'MDURATION function to calculate the modified duration of a bond', 'answer': 'Use the MDURATION function to calculate the modified duration of a bond. Example formula: =MDURATION(settlement, maturity, coupon, yld, frequency, [basis]}, where settlement is the bond\'s settlement date, maturity is the bond\'s maturity date, coupon is the bond\'s annual coupon rate, yld is the bond\'s annual yield, frequency is the number of coupon payments per year, and basis is the day count basis.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'How to calculate depreciation?', 'answer': 'Depreciation can be calculated using the SLN function for straight-line depreciation.'},
            {'category': 'Accounting', 'question': 'COUPNUM function to calculate the number of coupon payments remaining for a bond', 'answer': 'Use the COUPNUM function to calculate the number of coupon payments remaining before a bond matures. Example formula: =COUPNUM(settlement, maturity, frequency, [basis]}, where settlement is the bond\'s settlement date, maturity is the bond\'s maturity date, frequency is the number of coupon payments per year, and basis is the day count basis.'},
